window.CONTENT_SPRINT_2 = {"marketplace-architecture":{"summary":"Understand how you, your Sellers and your customers interact through Marketplacer, how the marketplace platform works with your ecommerce experience, and how product, Order, fulfilment, refund and financial information moves across the marketplace ecosystem.","audience":["Marketplace lead","Marketplace operations","Seller management","Catalogue","Customer service","Finance","Technology and integrations"],"sections":{"Operator, Seller and Customer":"<p>A multi-Seller marketplace brings together three primary participants: you as the Operator, the Sellers offering products or services, and the customers purchasing through your customer-facing experience. Each participant has different responsibilities, access and information.</p><div class=\"card-grid\"><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>You, as the Operator</h3><p>Define the marketplace model, configure the platform, onboard Sellers, govern the catalogue, coordinate customer and Seller operations, and oversee marketplace performance and finance.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Sellers</h3><p>Supply and maintain their Adverts and Variants, fulfil their Invoices, provide tracking, participate in cancellations and returns, and meet the standards in the Seller agreement.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Customers</h3><p>Browse, purchase, receive delivery updates, request support and follow the cancellation and return experience provided by your marketplace.</p></article></div><h3>One customer Order can involve several Sellers</h3><pre><code>Customer Order\n├── Seller A Invoice\n│   ├── Line Item 1\n│   └── Line Item 2\n└── Seller B Invoice\n    └── Line Item 3</code></pre><p>The customer may see one Order, while each Seller receives only the Invoice and Line Items associated with its own products. Those Invoices can be dispatched at different times, through different carriers and with separate tracking numbers.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Activity</th><th>Operator responsibility</th><th>Seller responsibility</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Marketplace policy</td><td>Define and approve the policy</td><td>Apply the policy to Seller operations</td></tr><tr><td>Seller account</td><td>Create and configure the account</td><td>Supply accurate business information</td></tr><tr><td>Product data</td><td>Set standards and governance</td><td>Supply and maintain compliant data</td></tr><tr><td>Fulfilment</td><td>Monitor service levels and exceptions</td><td>Dispatch products and provide tracking</td></tr><tr><td>Customer support</td><td>Provide or coordinate the customer response</td><td>Provide operational information and actions</td></tr><tr><td>Marketplace finance</td><td>Configure and reconcile calculations</td><td>Review Remittances and raise queries</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Define the responsibility boundaries before launch.</strong> Document who owns customer communication, Seller communication, product quality, fulfilment exceptions, payment refunds and financial reconciliation.</div>","Marketplace Platform vs Ecommerce Front End":"<p>Marketplacer provides the marketplace management and operational layer. Your ecommerce platform provides the customer-facing digital experience. The complete solution may also include payment, shipping, customer-service, finance and reporting systems.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Marketplacer commonly manages</th><th>Your ecommerce experience commonly manages</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Seller accounts and Seller settings</td><td>Website design and content</td></tr><tr><td>Adverts, Variants, mapping and product vetting</td><td>Navigation, search and merchandising</td></tr><tr><td>Commission, wholesale and Remittance records</td><td>Customer accounts, cart and checkout</td></tr><tr><td>Orders, Seller Invoices and Line Items</td><td>Customer payment experience</td></tr><tr><td>Shipments, Refund Requests and Seller adjustments</td><td>Customer emails, loyalty and service interfaces</td></tr><tr><td>Seller performance, APIs and webhooks</td><td>First-party products and other retail capabilities</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h3>Capabilities delivered across your marketplace ecosystem</h3><p>Your complete marketplace solution may also include capabilities delivered through your ecommerce platform, connected systems, third-party providers or custom integrations, including:</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Website design and content management</li><li>Customer accounts</li><li>Search implementation</li><li>Cart and checkout experience</li><li>Payment processing</li><li>Loyalty programmes</li><li>Customer-service platforms</li><li>Marketing automation</li><li>Carrier labels and shipping services</li><li>Accounting and general-ledger systems</li></ul><p>During solution design, confirm which system provides each capability, how it connects to Marketplacer and which team owns its ongoing operation.</p><h3>Product publication flow</h3><div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Seller source</strong><p>The Seller creates or maintains the product in the agreed source system.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Marketplacer ingestion</strong><p>The Advert and Variants enter Marketplacer.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Mapping and governance</strong><p>The product aligns to your Categories, Brands, Option Types and product standards.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Ecommerce synchronisation</strong><p>The approved product is sent to the customer-facing platform.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>Customer experience</strong><p>The product appears in navigation, search, product pages and checkout.</p></div></div></div><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>A stable marketplace taxonomy can support many customer-facing experiences.</strong> The ecommerce team can create collections, campaigns and navigation without reproducing every temporary merchandising concept in the core Marketplacer taxonomy.</div>","Operator Portal":"<p>The Operator Portal is the administration environment used by your authorised internal teams and partners to configure and operate the marketplace.</p><div class=\"card-grid\"><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Configuration</h3><p>Manage site details, Seller settings, finance settings, Commission Packages, shipping, refund reasons, email settings and other marketplace-wide controls.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Marketplace structure</h3><p>Create and maintain Categories, Prototypes, Option Types, Option Values and Brands.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Seller management</h3><p>Create Sellers, configure permissions and commercial arrangements, review activity and manage Seller status.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Catalogue governance</h3><p>Review mapping, Catalog Rules, product vetting, Golden Products and catalogue-quality issues.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Orders and refunds</h3><p>Review Orders, Invoices, Line Items, Shipments and Refund Requests, and coordinate operational exceptions.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Finance and reporting</h3><p>Review sales, Remittances, Seller financial records and operational reports.</p></article></div><h3>Production and Sandbox</h3><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Sandbox</th><th>Production</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Use for learning, sample Sellers, sample products and controlled testing</td><td>Use for live Sellers, products, Orders and financial records</td></tr><tr><td>Validate configuration and integrations before release</td><td>Apply only approved and tested changes</td></tr><tr><td>Treat data as test data</td><td>Protect access and maintain evidence for sensitive changes</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h3>Role-based access</h3><p>Create roles that match the work each user performs. Catalogue reviewers, customer-service users, finance users and platform administrators may require different permissions.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Use individual accounts</li><li>Restrict sensitive finance and Production permissions</li><li>Review user access regularly</li><li>Remove access promptly when responsibilities change</li><li>Confirm the environment before making a change</li></ul><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Production changes can affect live Sellers, products, Orders and financial records.</strong> Complete the required approval, testing and verification before applying a change in Production.</div>","Seller Portal":"<p>The Seller Portal is the workspace provided to each Seller. A Seller sees only its own account, Adverts, Variants, Invoices, Shipments, Refund Requests and financial information according to its permissions and connection method.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Area</th><th>Seller activity</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Account and users</td><td>Maintain business details, contacts, users and permitted settings</td></tr><tr><td>Products</td><td>Create or review Adverts and Variants, complete mapping and correct product errors</td></tr><tr><td>Orders and fulfilment</td><td>Review Invoices, dispatch Line Items, enter carriers and tracking</td></tr><tr><td>Returns and refunds</td><td>Complete the Seller actions enabled for cancellations and post-dispatch returns</td></tr><tr><td>Finance and reporting</td><td>Review sales, Remittances and Seller-specific reports</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h3>Seller Portal and connected source systems</h3><p>An integrated Seller may maintain products, stock, pricing and fulfilment in Shopify, WooCommerce, an ERP or another approved source. The Seller Portal remains useful for account settings, mapping, product errors, Refund Requests, Remittances and operational exceptions.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Connection method</th><th>Typical product workflow</th><th>Typical fulfilment workflow</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Seller Portal</td><td>Managed directly in Marketplacer</td><td>Managed directly in Marketplacer</td></tr><tr><td>Bulk Product Management</td><td>Prepared and uploaded in a spreadsheet</td><td>Seller Portal or an approved bulk process</td></tr><tr><td>MConnect</td><td>Synchronised from the supported Seller platform</td><td>Completed in the connected Seller platform where supported</td></tr><tr><td>API or middleware</td><td>Managed through the custom integration</td><td>Managed through the custom integration</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h3>Seller onboarding and permissions</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Confirm Seller users and individual access</li><li>Assign the correct commercial and operational settings</li><li>Confirm the product-ingestion and fulfilment methods</li><li>Tailor training to the Seller’s day-to-day responsibilities</li><li>Explain support and escalation routes</li><li>Enable cancellation, refund and shipping permissions only where the operating model supports them</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Connection method should shape Seller training.</strong> Focus training on the activities the Seller will actually complete in the Seller Portal and the exceptions it may need to manage there.</div>","Connected Systems":"<p>A marketplace usually connects Marketplacer with several systems. Document the responsibility and ownership of each connection before development and testing begin.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Connected system</th><th>Possible responsibilities</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ecommerce platform</td><td>Customer-facing products, search, cart, checkout, payment and customer accounts</td></tr><tr><td>Seller platforms</td><td>Seller product, price, inventory, Order and fulfilment information</td></tr><tr><td>PIM, ERP or product services</td><td>Product enrichment, identifiers, catalogue or commercial data</td></tr><tr><td>Payment and payout providers</td><td>Customer transactions, refunds, settlement and Seller payout</td></tr><tr><td>Shipping and fulfilment systems</td><td>Labels, warehouse activity, carrier updates and tracking</td></tr><tr><td>Customer-service platform</td><td>Customer cases, communication and escalation</td></tr><tr><td>Finance and data platforms</td><td>Accounting, reconciliation, analytics and reporting</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h3>Integration methods</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>MConnect</li><li>Operator API</li><li>Seller API</li><li>Webhooks</li><li>Scheduled files</li><li>Bulk spreadsheets</li><li>Middleware or integration platform</li><li>Manual fallback processes</li></ul><h3>Connected-system register</h3><p>Maintain one register containing the purpose, source data, destination, business owner, technical owner, update frequency, identifiers, monitoring and fallback for every launch-critical system.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Control</th><th>Question to answer</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Source of truth</td><td>Which system owns the field or process?</td></tr><tr><td>Trigger and frequency</td><td>What starts the flow and how quickly should it complete?</td></tr><tr><td>Identifiers</td><td>How is one record matched across systems?</td></tr><tr><td>Monitoring</td><td>Who is alerted when processing fails or becomes delayed?</td></tr><tr><td>Retry and correction</td><td>How can failed or incorrect records be safely recovered?</td></tr><tr><td>Manual fallback</td><td>How will the business continue while the connection is unavailable?</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>A connection is operationally ready when it can be monitored and recovered.</strong> A successful first data transfer should be followed by failure testing, alerting, reconciliation and a documented support owner.</div>","Marketplace Data Flow":"<p>Marketplace data moves through several connected flows. Each flow should have an identified source, destination, owner, control and reconciliation method.</p><h3>Seller and product flow</h3><pre><code>Seller recruited\n        ↓\nSeller account configured\n        ↓\nAdvert and Variants ingested\n        ↓\nMapping and Catalog Rules\n        ↓\nProduct vetting where enabled\n        ↓\nMarketplacer publication\n        ↓\nEcommerce publication</code></pre><h3>Order and fulfilment flow</h3><pre><code>Customer completes checkout\n        ↓\nMarketplace Order created\n        ↓\nSeller Invoices and Line Items created\n        ↓\nSeller fulfils each Invoice\n        ↓\nShipments and tracking recorded\n        ↓\nCustomer experience updated</code></pre><h3>Cancellation and return flow</h3><p>A pre-dispatch cancellation and a post-dispatch return follow different operational paths, but both must keep the Marketplacer workflow, customer payment outcome and Seller financial adjustment aligned.</p><h3>Financial flow</h3><pre><code>Customer transaction\n        ↓\nOrder and Seller Invoices\n        ↓\nCommission, fees, tax and adjustments\n        ↓\nInvoice completion\n        ↓\nRemittance eligibility and approval\n        ↓\nSeller payout process</code></pre><h3>Data-flow documentation</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Source and destination</li><li>Trigger and expected timing</li><li>Required fields and identifiers</li><li>Business and technical owners</li><li>Error handling and monitoring</li><li>Reconciliation control</li><li>Manual fallback</li><li>Security and access</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Test the boundaries between systems.</strong> A complete test should prove Seller creation, product ingestion, mapping, publication, checkout, Order creation, Seller fulfilment, tracking, cancellation or return, payment refund, Seller adjustment and Remittance reporting.</div>"},"related":[["marketplace-terminology","Marketplace Terminology"],["end-to-end-flow","End-to-End Marketplace Flow"],["integration-architecture","Integration Architecture"]]},"marketplace-terminology":{"summary":"Learn the core Marketplacer terms used across catalogue management, Orders, fulfilment, refunds and marketplace finance. Using the correct record name helps teams investigate issues accurately and select the right identifier.","audience":["Marketplace operations","Seller management","Catalogue","Customer service","Finance","Technology and integrations"],"sections":{"Advert, Commonly Called a Product":"<p>An <strong>Advert</strong> is placed by a Seller and represents an item offered for sale. In everyday Operator and Seller conversations, Adverts are commonly called <strong>products</strong>. In platform configuration, APIs and technical investigations, Advert is the more precise record name.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Belongs to one Seller</li><li>Contains product-level title, description, images and attributes</li><li>Has an Advert type such as product, event, service or holiday</li><li>Contains one or more Variants</li><li>Can be mapped, validated, vetted and published</li><li>May be linked to a Golden Product</li></ul><pre><code>Seller\n└── Advert (product)\n    ├── Variant A\n    ├── Variant B\n    └── Variant C</code></pre><h3>Advert status</h3><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Status</th><th>General meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Online</td><td>Available for customers to view and purchase</td></tr><tr><td>Not Published</td><td>Not currently live</td></tr><tr><td>Invalid</td><td>Required information needs to be completed or corrected</td></tr><tr><td>Not Displayed, No Stock</td><td>Not displayed because no sellable stock is available</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Two Sellers offering the same physical item have separate Adverts.</strong> Their Adverts may later be linked to the same Golden Product, while each Seller retains its own price, inventory and fulfilment responsibility.</div>","Variant":"<p>A <strong>Variant</strong> is an individual purchasable version of an Advert. It represents the exact size, colour, configuration or other option selected by the customer.</p><pre><code>Advert: Classic Cotton T-Shirt\n├── Variant: Black / Small\n├── Variant: Black / Medium\n└── Variant: White / Medium</code></pre><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>SKU</li><li>GTIN, EAN or barcode</li><li>Price and recommended retail price</li><li>Wholesale price where used</li><li>Inventory or count on hand</li><li>Variant Option Values</li><li>Shipping profile and weight</li><li>Tax information</li><li>Variant status</li></ul><p>When a customer purchases a marketplace product, the selected Variant becomes a Line Item in an Invoice.</p>","Seller":"<p>A <strong>Seller</strong> is the business offering Adverts through your marketplace. Each Seller has its own Marketplacer account, settings, users, products, Invoices, Refund Requests and financial records.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Business and store information</li><li>Commission Package or wholesale arrangement</li><li>Remittance and payout settings</li><li>Shipping configuration</li><li>Cancellation and refund permissions</li><li>Product-vetting requirement</li><li>Dispatch SLA</li><li>Integration method</li></ul><p>Seller responsibilities depend on the agreement and operating model, but commonly include product accuracy, inventory, fulfilment, tracking, return actions and performance standards.</p>","Operator":"<p>The <strong>Operator</strong> is the organisation that runs the marketplace. Within this Hub, <strong>you</strong> normally refers to the Operator.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Marketplace strategy and business model</li><li>Seller proposition and commercial terms</li><li>Customer policies</li><li>Catalogue structure and product standards</li><li>Shipping and refund processes</li><li>Financial controls and reconciliation</li><li>Integration responsibilities</li><li>Seller-performance expectations</li><li>Launch and day-to-day operations</li></ul><p>Authorised users perform marketplace administration through the Operator Portal.</p>","Order":"<p>An <strong>Order</strong> is the result of a customer completing checkout for one or more marketplace Adverts. An Order contains one or more Invoices, and each Invoice contains one or more Line Items.</p><pre><code>Order\n├── Invoice: Seller A\n│   ├── Line Item 1\n│   └── Line Item 2\n└── Invoice: Seller B\n    └── Line Item 3</code></pre><p>Retain the identifiers that connect the ecommerce Order, Marketplacer Order, Seller Invoices, payment transaction and any Seller source-system Order.</p>","Invoice":"<p>An <strong>Invoice</strong> represents the part of an Order handled by one Seller. Even when only one Seller participates, the Order still contains a Seller Invoice.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Belongs to one Seller</li><li>Contains one or more Line Items</li><li>Supports Seller fulfilment and financial calculations</li><li>Can have several Shipments</li><li>Can be affected by cancellations, returns and refunds</li><li>Progresses toward Remittance once eligible</li></ul><p>A separate Invoice may also be created for different delivery methods, such as Buy Online and Click and Collect, even when the items belong to the same Seller.</p><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Use the full term when needed.</strong> A Marketplacer Seller Invoice is different from a customer tax invoice, payment receipt, commission invoice or Remittance advice.</div>","Line Item":"<p>A <strong>Line Item</strong> represents the purchase of an individual Variant or other purchasable item. A Line Item belongs to an Invoice and includes the purchased quantity.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Purchased Variant</li><li>Quantity</li><li>Item value and tax</li><li>Postage allocation</li><li>Promotion adjustment</li><li>Commission and merchant fee components</li><li>Shipment quantity</li><li>Refund and financial adjustment information</li></ul><p>Many marketplace actions occur at Line Item level, including partial Shipment, cancellation, return, refund and Seller financial adjustment.</p>","Shipment":"<p>A <strong>Shipment</strong> records the dispatch of some or all Line Items or quantities belonging to an Invoice.</p><pre><code>Invoice\n├── Shipment 1: Line Item A and part of Line Item B\n└── Shipment 2: Remaining quantity of Line Item B</code></pre><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Carrier</li><li>Tracking number</li><li>Dispatch date</li><li>Included Line Items and quantities</li><li>Shipment status</li></ul><p>One Invoice can have several Shipments. The Invoice reaches completion once all quantities have been dispatched, cancelled or otherwise resolved through the approved workflow.</p>","Refund Request":"<p>A <strong>Refund Request</strong> is the Marketplacer workflow record used to manage a pre-dispatch cancellation, a post-dispatch return or a returnless refund.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Status</th><th>General meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Awaiting</td><td>A Seller decision, physical return or return-processing action remains outstanding</td></tr><tr><td>Processed</td><td>The request is ready for Operator finalisation</td></tr><tr><td>Refunded</td><td>The Marketplacer workflow has been finalised</td></tr><tr><td>Denied</td><td>All affected refund line items have been declined</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Marketplacer records the workflow and related Seller financial adjustments. Complete the customer payment refund through the configured payment-provider process and reconcile both outcomes.</p>","Commission":"<p><strong>Commission</strong> is the amount calculated for the Operator under a commission-based marketplace model.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Default Commission Package rate</li><li>Seller-specific package</li><li>Category or other specific rate</li><li>Price-based rule</li><li>Scheduled rate change</li><li>Commission on postage where configured</li></ul><pre><code>Item value: $100\nCommission rate: 20%\nCommission: $20</code></pre><p>Your refund policy and configuration determine whether commission is reversed, retained or recalculated when an item is cancelled or returned.</p>","Remittance":"<p>A <strong>Remittance</strong> represents the amount calculated as payable to a Seller after relevant deductions, withholdings and adjustments.</p><pre><code>Seller item value\n+ Seller postage\n- Commission\n- Merchant fees\n- Refund adjustments\n- Tax withheld\n- Other adjustments\n= Seller Remittance</code></pre><p>Remittance and payout are connected but distinct. Remittance is the marketplace calculation; payout is the movement of funds through the configured payment or banking process.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Remittance delay may apply globally or to an individual Seller</li><li>Automatic or manual payout approval may apply</li><li>Refunds can reduce a current or future Remittance</li><li>Finance should reconcile Remittance advice, payout and accounting records</li></ul>","Golden Product":"<p>A <strong>Golden Product</strong>, also called a Golden Record in some material, is a central product record held in the Central Product Database. It can provide baseline information and link equivalent Seller Adverts.</p><pre><code>Golden Product\n└── Golden Product Variant\n    ├── Seller A Advert Variant\n    └── Seller B Advert Variant</code></pre><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Standardised product title, description, images and attributes</li><li>Consolidation of equivalent Seller offers</li><li>Product enrichment</li><li>Faster product creation using baseline information</li><li>Multiple-offer or buy-box experiences</li></ul><p>The Golden Product itself is not purchased. Customers purchase a Variant belonging to a Seller Advert.</p><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Product and Product Item have a specialist meaning in the Central Product Database.</strong> Use Golden Product and Golden Product Variant in Operator guidance unless a specific screen, export or API uses Product or Product Item.</div>"},"related":[["marketplace-architecture","Marketplace Architecture"],["end-to-end-flow","End-to-End Marketplace Flow"],["product-model","Product Model"]]},"end-to-end-flow":{"summary":"Follow the marketplace journey from Seller creation through product onboarding, customer purchase, fulfilment, cancellations, returns, refunds and Remittance. Use the flow to assign owners and test every handoff.","audience":["Marketplace operations","Seller management","Catalogue","Ecommerce","Customer service","Finance","Technology and integrations"],"sections":{"Seller Creation":"<p>Seller creation establishes the account that will own Adverts, receive Invoices, fulfil Line Items and participate in marketplace finance.</p><p>Confirm the Seller’s core commercial and operational arrangements before account creation so the correct commission, Remittance, shipping, refund and permission settings can be applied from the start.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Legal and trading names</li><li>Business, operational and finance contacts</li><li>Seller users</li><li>Agreement status</li><li>Commission Package or wholesale arrangement</li><li>Tax and merchant-fee treatment</li><li>Remittance delay and payout approval</li><li>Shipping approach and dispatch SLA</li><li>Product-ingestion method</li><li>Product vetting and refund permissions</li><li>Product scope and target launch date</li></ul><div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Collect and approve information</strong><p>Confirm the commercial, legal, product and operational position.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Create and configure the Seller</strong><p>Apply the approved Seller settings in the correct environment.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Invite users</strong><p>Provide individual access and confirm successful sign-in.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Enable the connection method</strong><p>Prepare Seller Portal, Bulk Product Management, MConnect or API access.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>Train and assign actions</strong><p>Explain product, fulfilment, refund, reporting and support responsibilities.</p></div></div></div><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Seller creation is complete when product onboarding can begin.</strong> The account, access, configuration, connection method and responsibilities should all be understood.</div>","Product Ingestion":"<p>Product ingestion brings a Seller’s Adverts and Variants into Marketplacer.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Best suited to</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Seller Portal</td><td>Small ranges and direct manual maintenance</td></tr><tr><td>Bulk Product Management</td><td>Structured bulk creation or updates using spreadsheets</td></tr><tr><td>MConnect</td><td>Supported Seller ecommerce platforms with ongoing synchronisation</td></tr><tr><td>Seller API or middleware</td><td>Custom, high-volume or specialist integrations</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>The selected method should reflect Seller technology, product volume, catalogue complexity, update frequency, launch timing and ongoing source-of-truth ownership.</p><h3>A successful import is one stage of onboarding</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Confirm the intended Adverts and Variants were created</li><li>Retain Seller source identifiers</li><li>Review unsuccessful records and assign corrections</li><li>Confirm price and inventory</li><li>Continue through mapping, Catalog Rules, product vetting and publication</li></ul>","Mapping":"<p>Mapping aligns Seller-supplied values with your approved Marketplacer catalogue structure. A confirmed mapping can be reused for later imports containing the same source value.</p><pre><code>Seller Category: Mens Trainers\n        ↓\nMarketplace Category: Footwear &gt; Athletic Shoes</code></pre><pre><code>Seller colour: Charcoal\n        ↓\nMarketplace Option Value: Black</code></pre><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Categories</li><li>Brands</li><li>Advert Option Types</li><li>Variant Option Types</li><li>Option Values</li><li>Shipping profiles and other controlled fields</li></ul><p>Assign ownership for unmapped values, new Brand or Option Value requests, incorrect mappings and ongoing mapping queues.</p><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Mapping creates consistency without forcing every Seller to use identical source terminology.</strong> Verify that reusable mappings are precise enough to apply safely to future imports.</div>","Product Vetting":"<p>Product vetting provides an Operator approval workflow before Seller products become available to customers. Catalog Rules can validate repeatable data requirements before or alongside human review.</p><pre><code>Product created or updated\n        ↓\nCatalog Rules validate Advert and Variants\n        ↓\nSeller corrects any failures\n        ↓\nOperator vetting where enabled\n        ↓\nApproved product progresses online</code></pre><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Title and description</li><li>Images</li><li>Category, Brand and Prototype</li><li>Advert and Variant attributes</li><li>Variant structure</li><li>Price and inventory</li><li>Tax and shipping information</li><li>Restricted-product or compliance requirements</li></ul><p>Provide specific rejection guidance that identifies the field, issue, required correction and resubmission path.</p><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Define which later product changes require review.</strong> Consider the effect of source-system synchronisation when reviewing or manually editing connected products.</div>","Publishing":"<p>Publishing makes an approved Seller Advert available through the connected customer experience.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Valid Advert and at least one valid Variant</li><li>Correct Category and Prototype</li><li>Required Option Values</li><li>Price and sellable inventory</li><li>Completed mapping</li><li>Catalog Rule compliance</li><li>Product-vetting approval where enabled</li><li>Online status in Marketplacer</li><li>Successful ecommerce synchronisation</li></ul><h3>Verify Marketplacer and the storefront</h3><p>Confirm the Advert is online in Marketplacer and that the customer-facing platform displays the correct title, images, Variants, price, inventory, Seller information, shipping promise, search and checkout behaviour.</p>","Order Creation":"<p>An Order is created when the customer completes checkout and the marketplace Order is submitted to Marketplacer.</p><pre><code>Customer completes checkout\n        ↓\nEcommerce completes its payment flow\n        ↓\nIntegration submits the marketplace Order\n        ↓\nMarketplacer creates the Order, Invoices and Line Items</code></pre><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Customer and delivery details</li><li>Variant and quantity</li><li>Item value, shipping, tax and promotion</li><li>Payment state required by the implementation</li><li>External ecommerce Order identifier</li></ul><h3>Monitor Order creation</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Failed or duplicate submission</li><li>Invalid Variant or insufficient inventory</li><li>Incorrect Seller, value, tax or shipping</li><li>Payment completed without a Marketplacer Order</li><li>Marketplacer Order created without the expected ecommerce update</li><li>Missing cross-system identifiers</li></ul>","Order Splitting":"<p>Marketplacer separates the customer Order into Seller-level Invoices. Each Invoice contains the Line Items handled by that Seller.</p><pre><code>Order\n├── Invoice: Seller One\n│   ├── Line Item A\n│   └── Line Item B\n└── Invoice: Seller Two\n    └── Line Item C</code></pre><p>Additional Invoice separation can occur for different delivery methods, such as Buy Online and Click and Collect, even when the same Seller supplies the items.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Verify every Line Item belongs to the correct Seller</li><li>Confirm delivery-method separation</li><li>Confirm Seller systems receive the expected records</li><li>Check that no marketplace item is duplicated or omitted</li></ul>","Fulfilment":"<p>Fulfilment begins when the Seller receives its Invoice and prepares the purchased Line Items for dispatch or collection.</p><div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Seller receives the Invoice</strong><p>The Seller or connected system receives the work.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Seller prepares the products</strong><p>Inventory and quantities are confirmed.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Shipment is created</strong><p>The Seller records the dispatched Line Items and quantities.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Carrier and tracking are added</strong><p>Marketplacer and the ecommerce experience receive the update.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>Customer is informed</strong><p>The customer receives the expected dispatch and tracking communication.</p></div></div></div><p>One Invoice can have several Shipments. Every quantity must eventually be dispatched, cancelled or otherwise resolved through the approved workflow.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Orders awaiting dispatch</li><li>Dispatch SLA breaches</li><li>Partial Shipments</li><li>Missing or invalid tracking</li><li>Integration failures</li><li>Shipment updates missing from ecommerce</li></ul>","Returns and Refunds":"<p>Use the cancellation workflow before dispatch and the post-dispatch return workflow after the product has been shipped.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Pre-dispatch cancellation</th><th>Post-dispatch return</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Select the eligible undispatched Line Item and quantity</td><td>Assess eligibility and whether a physical return is required</td></tr><tr><td>Complete Seller action where required</td><td>Seller receives or assesses the return where required</td></tr><tr><td>Finalise the marketplace adjustment</td><td>Finalise the Refund Request and marketplace adjustment</td></tr><tr><td>Complete and reconcile the customer payment refund</td><td>Complete and reconcile the customer payment refund</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Confirm that the Marketplacer workflow, customer payment outcome, Seller financial adjustment, inventory treatment and customer communication all agree.</p><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Marketplace workflow and movement of customer funds are connected controls.</strong> Complete the payment-provider refund and reconcile it with the finalised Marketplacer Refund Request.</div>","Remittance":"<p>Remittance calculates the amount payable to a Seller for eligible completed activity after commission, fees, refunds and other adjustments.</p>\n<h3>How Remittance progresses</h3>\n<div class=\"process-flow\">\n  <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Seller completes the Invoice</strong><p>The relevant fulfilment or completion event occurs.</p></div></div>\n  <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Release requirement is satisfied</strong><p>The Invoice meets the configured release condition for Remittance.</p></div></div>\n  <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Remittance delay passes</strong><p>Any marketplace-wide or Seller-specific delay period is completed.</p></div></div>\n  <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Scheduled processing occurs</strong><p>Marketplacer calculates the payable amount during the configured processing cycle.</p></div></div>\n  <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>Remittance advice is generated</strong><p>The Seller financial statement is produced for review and reconciliation.</p></div></div>\n  <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">6</span><div><strong>Configured payout process progresses</strong><p>The movement of funds follows the marketplace's approved payout method and controls.</p></div></div>\n</div>\n<h3>How the Remittance amount is calculated</h3>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\">\n  <thead><tr><th>Adjustment</th><th>Component</th><th>Effect</th></tr></thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr><td><strong>+</strong></td><td>Eligible Seller item value</td><td>Included</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><strong>+</strong></td><td>Eligible Seller postage</td><td>Included</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><strong>−</strong></td><td>Commission</td><td>Deducted</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><strong>−</strong></td><td>Merchant fees</td><td>Deducted</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><strong>−</strong></td><td>Refund adjustments</td><td>Deducted</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><strong>−</strong></td><td>Tax withheld</td><td>Deducted</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><strong>±</strong></td><td>Other adjustments</td><td>Applied as relevant</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><strong>=</strong></td><td><strong>Seller Remittance</strong></td><td><strong>Final calculated amount payable</strong></td></tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table></div>\n<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Review incomplete Invoices</li><li>Review Remittances awaiting release</li><li>Confirm Remittance delays and schedules</li><li>Investigate negative Seller balances</li><li>Reconcile Remittance advice and payout</li><li>Include refunds and later adjustments</li></ul>\n<div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Remittance is the calculated marketplace amount; payout moves the funds.</strong> Where MPay is enabled, payout processing forms part of the integrated MPay flow. Other implementations may use an external provider or finance process.</div>"},"related":[["marketplace-architecture","Marketplace Architecture"],["marketplace-terminology","Marketplace Terminology"],["end-to-end-testing","End-to-End Testing"]]},"roles-responsibilities":{"summary":"Define who owns the decisions, configuration, Seller relationships, catalogue standards, customer support, financial controls and connected systems required to launch and operate your marketplace.","audience":["Marketplace leadership","Marketplace operations","Seller management","Catalogue","Finance","Customer service","Technology and integrations","Project managers"],"sections":{"Marketplace Leadership":"<p>Marketplace leadership owns the overall direction, priorities and accountability of the marketplace.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Marketplace strategy and business objective</li><li>Launch scope and success measures</li><li>Business and operating model</li><li>Decision governance and escalation</li><li>Resourcing and investment</li><li>Acceptance of launch risk</li><li>Go-live approval</li><li>Post-launch review cadence</li></ul><h3>Go-live approval</h3><p>Approve launch once critical decisions are closed, Production configuration is complete, live Sellers and products are ready, end-to-end testing has passed, operational teams are prepared and known risks have owners and accepted treatments.</p><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Name the accountable marketplace owner.</strong> The programme needs a person with authority to resolve cross-team decisions and accept the final launch position.</div>","Marketplace Operations":"<p>Marketplace operations coordinates the work connecting Sellers, products, Orders, customers, finance and integrations. It turns approved business decisions into repeatable platform configuration and operating processes.</p><div class=\"card-grid\"><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Platform coordination</h3><p>Coordinate environments, users, Seller settings, finance configuration, taxonomy, shipping, refunds and testing.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Seller onboarding</h3><p>Progress each Seller from approved prospect through configuration, connection, products, testing and launch.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Operational exceptions</h3><p>Coordinate product, fulfilment, refund, finance and integration issues.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Marketplace health</h3><p>Monitor daily queues, Seller activity, product quality, Order exceptions and customer impact.</p></article></div><h3>Decision owner and configuration owner</h3><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Configuration</th><th>Typical decision owner</th><th>Typical configuration owner</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Commission rate</td><td>Commercial and finance</td><td>Marketplace operations</td></tr><tr><td>Return reasons</td><td>Customer service or policy owner</td><td>Marketplace operations</td></tr><tr><td>Dispatch SLA</td><td>Seller management</td><td>Marketplace operations</td></tr><tr><td>Taxonomy</td><td>Catalogue</td><td>Catalogue or marketplace operations</td></tr><tr><td>API permissions</td><td>Technology</td><td>Authorised platform administrator</td></tr><tr><td>Remittance delay</td><td>Finance and commercial</td><td>Marketplace operations</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Maintain the Marketplace Decision Register</li><li>Maintain the Seller onboarding tracker</li><li>Control Production access and changes</li><li>Monitor product, Order, refund and integration queues</li><li>Coordinate incidents and escalation</li><li>Prepare the transition into business-as-usual operations</li></ul>","Seller Management":"<p>Seller management owns the commercial and relationship aspects of the Seller lifecycle.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Seller proposition and target profile</li><li>Recruitment, qualification and pipeline</li><li>Seller agreement and commercial discussions</li><li>Commercial-readiness handoff</li><li>Onboarding communication</li><li>Seller-performance reviews</li><li>Growth opportunities</li><li>Suspension or exit recommendations</li></ul><h3>Handoff to marketplace operations</h3><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Seller management provides</th><th>Marketplace operations completes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Approved Seller details and contacts</td><td>Seller account creation and access</td></tr><tr><td>Agreement status and commercial terms</td><td>Approved Seller configuration</td></tr><tr><td>Product scope and connection method</td><td>Product and integration onboarding coordination</td></tr><tr><td>Target date and known risks</td><td>Operational plan, tracker and launch checks</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Early Sellers may require additional onboarding assistance. Define the ongoing support boundary so Sellers understand which activities remain their responsibility after launch.</p><h3>Performance escalation</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Operational guidance for isolated issues</li><li>Corrective action for repeated SLA or data-quality concerns</li><li>Commercial escalation for unresolved terms or material risk</li><li>Suspension or exit for serious or persistent breach</li></ul>","Catalogue Team":"<p>The catalogue team owns the structure, quality and governance of marketplace product information.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Categories and taxonomy</li><li>Prototypes</li><li>Advert and Variant Option Types</li><li>Option Values</li><li>Brands</li><li>Product-data and image standards</li><li>Catalog Rules</li><li>Mapping governance</li><li>Product vetting</li><li>Golden Product governance</li><li>Ongoing catalogue-quality audits</li></ul><h3>Catalogue and ecommerce merchandising</h3><p>The catalogue team governs stable product structure and data quality. The ecommerce or merchandising team may separately manage customer-facing navigation, collections, campaigns, search merchandising and seasonal presentation.</p><h3>Decision authority</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Who can create or change Categories and Prototypes</li><li>Who can add Option Types, Option Values and Brands</li><li>Who reviews and rejects Seller products</li><li>Who approves restricted products</li><li>Who can link or unlink Golden Products</li><li>Who changes product standards and Catalog Rules</li></ul>","Finance":"<p>Finance owns the integrity, reconciliation and governance of marketplace financial processes.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Commission, wholesale and merchant-fee policy</li><li>Tax treatment and withholding</li><li>Promotion funding</li><li>Remittance timing and payout approval</li><li>Refund financial treatment</li><li>Chargeback responsibility</li><li>Financial reporting standards</li><li>Reconciliation and discrepancy investigation</li></ul><h3>Configuration and approval</h3><p>Marketplace operations may apply approved finance settings in Marketplacer. Finance validates that the configured calculation reflects the commercial agreement and accounting treatment.</p><h3>Reconciliation</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Ecommerce Order totals</li><li>Payment transactions</li><li>Marketplacer Orders and Invoices</li><li>Refund Requests and payment refunds</li><li>Commission and merchant fees</li><li>Remittances and payouts</li><li>Accounting entries</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Separate configuration, approval and reconciliation.</strong> Sensitive financial processes are stronger when one person does not control every stage.</div>","Customer Service":"<p>Customer service owns the customer-facing response to questions involving Orders, fulfilment, cancellations, returns and refunds.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Order confirmation and status</li><li>Split Shipments and tracking</li><li>Delayed dispatch</li><li>Cancellation eligibility</li><li>Return instructions</li><li>Refund status</li><li>Damaged or incorrect products</li><li>Complaints and policy exceptions</li></ul><p>The customer-service team may continue working in its established service platform while using Marketplacer, ecommerce and Seller communication channels to obtain marketplace information.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Issue</th><th>Typical escalation</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Seller has not dispatched</td><td>Seller management or marketplace operations</td></tr><tr><td>Product information is misleading</td><td>Catalogue</td></tr><tr><td>Refund amount appears incorrect</td><td>Finance</td></tr><tr><td>Order did not reach the Seller</td><td>Technology and integrations</td></tr><tr><td>Suspected Marketplacer behaviour</td><td>Marketplace operations and Marketplacer Support</td></tr><tr><td>Policy exception</td><td>Customer-service policy owner</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Prepare cancellation and return policies</li><li>Prepare response templates</li><li>Define the Seller contact process</li><li>Define payment-refund and Marketplacer finalisation responsibilities</li><li>Train using representative test Orders</li></ul>","Technology and Integrations":"<p>Technology and integrations owns the systems and data flows connecting Marketplacer with the wider marketplace ecosystem.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Solution architecture</li><li>Source-of-truth implementation</li><li>Product, inventory and price synchronisation</li><li>Order creation and routing</li><li>Shipment and tracking updates</li><li>Refund integration</li><li>API and webhook security</li><li>Monitoring and alerting</li><li>Retry and data correction</li><li>Manual fallback and incident recovery</li></ul><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Technology responsibility</th><th>Marketplace operations responsibility</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Maintain technical data movement</td><td>Own the operational outcome</td></tr><tr><td>Investigate system errors and logs</td><td>Identify the Seller, customer and business impact</td></tr><tr><td>Maintain monitoring and retries</td><td>Monitor operational queues and exceptions</td></tr><tr><td>Restore the integration</td><td>Verify the complete marketplace process after recovery</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Assign both a business owner and technical owner to each integration.</strong> The business owner defines the required outcome; the technical owner maintains the data flow and recovery process.</div>","Marketplacer Delivery":"<p>Marketplacer Delivery guides your team through onboarding, platform enablement and launch preparation.</p><h3>Project initiation</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Production and Sandbox environment creation and initial preconfiguration</li><li>Environment Manager setup</li><li>Kickoff and onboarding checklist walkthrough</li><li>Training planning</li><li>Timeline and milestone alignment</li><li>Initial risk and dependency review</li></ul><h3>Discovery and enablement</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Customer Journey Mapping</li><li>Seller Strategy</li><li>Role-relevant platform training</li><li>Implementation guidance</li><li>Onboarding tracker review</li><li>Readiness and handover coordination</li></ul><h3>Your ownership during Delivery</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Business decisions and customer policies</li><li>Seller terms and recruitment</li><li>Front-end and integration delivery</li><li>Internal process design</li><li>Configuration completion</li><li>Seller and product onboarding</li><li>Testing participation</li><li>Go-live approval</li><li>Ongoing marketplace operations</li></ul><p>As onboarding concludes, Marketplacer Delivery coordinates the transition into Customer Success and Support, including marketplace status, live Sellers, remaining risks, key stakeholders and near-term priorities.</p>","Marketplacer Support":"<p>Marketplacer Support assists with suspected platform issues, unexpected behaviour and matters requiring product investigation.</p><h3>Your first-line support role</h3><ol><li>Confirm the expected workflow.</li><li>Review the affected Seller and marketplace configuration.</li><li>Collect the relevant record identifiers.</li><li>Check connected systems and integrations.</li><li>Assess customer, Seller and financial impact.</li><li>Complete appropriate internal troubleshooting.</li><li>Submit a Support request where Marketplacer investigation is required.</li></ol><h3>Include in a Support request</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Production or Sandbox</li><li>Marketplace and Seller</li><li>Advert, Variant, Order, Invoice or other affected identifiers</li><li>Date, time and timezone</li><li>Expected and actual behaviour</li><li>Screenshots and error messages</li><li>Integration logs or webhook details</li><li>Business impact</li><li>Troubleshooting completed</li></ul><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Marketplacer team</th><th>Primary focus</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Delivery</td><td>Onboarding, training and launch preparation</td></tr><tr><td>Customer Success</td><td>Ongoing relationship, adoption and strategic guidance</td></tr><tr><td>Support</td><td>Product investigation and issue resolution</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Sellers and customers should ordinarily contact your organisation first.</strong> Your marketplace team can resolve operational matters and provide Marketplacer Support with a complete, well-triaged investigation request when needed.</div>"},"related":[["marketplace-architecture","Marketplace Architecture"],["onboarding-overview","Operator and Marketplacer Responsibilities"],["getting-support","Getting Support"]]}};
